# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: engine-control-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:engine-control-unit/air-fuel-ratio-meter] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:engine-control-unit/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:engine-control-unit/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] In internal combustion engines with turbochargers, an **anti-lag system** (**ALS**) is a method of reducing turbo lag in racing or performance applications.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] It works by retarding ignition timing and adding extra fuel (and sometimes air) to balance an inherent loss in combustion efficiency with increased pressure at the turbine.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The excess fuel/air mixture escapes through the exhaust valves and combusts in the hot exhaust manifold, spooling the turbocharger and creating higher usable pressure.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] ALSes were first used in the early days of turbocharging in Formula One in the 1980s until fuel restrictions made their use unsuitable.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The technology later became common in rally cars because of increased turbo lag from the mandated restrictor plate at the intake.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The restrictor results in a significant intake pressure drop; the pressure ratio for a given boost level is much higher, and the turbocharger must spin much faster to produce the same boost as it would unrestricted, significantly increasing turbo lag.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] An ALS requires an air bypass, generally done in one of two ways.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The first method is to use a throttle air bypass that circumvents the throttle and feeds air to the engine; this may be an external bypass valve or a solenoid that slightly opens the throttle 12–20 degrees.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The second method is to use a bypass that feeds charge air (pressurized intake air between the turbo compressor and intake valves) directly to the exhaust manifold.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The throttle bypass or "throttle kick" system is combined with ignition timing retardation and slight fuel enrichment (mainly to provide cooling).
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Typically, ignition occurs at 35–45° ATDC (after top dead center).
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This late ignition causes very little expansion of the gas in the cylinder, so that the pressure and temperature are kept high when the exhaust valve opens.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] At the same time, the amount of torque delivered to the crankshaft is very small (just enough to keep the engine running).
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The higher exhaust pressure and temperature, combined with increased mass flow, are enough to keep the turbocharger spinning at high speed.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] When the throttle is opened up, ignition and fuel injection return to normal.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Since many engine components are exposed to extreme temperatures and high-pressure pulses during ALS operation, this kind of system places a large amount of stress on the engine, turbocharger, and exhaust manifold.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] In addition to temperature issues, uncontrolled turbo speeds can quickly destroy the turbocharger.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] In most applications, the ALS is automatically deactivated to prevent overheating when the coolant reaches a temperature of 110–115 °C.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] An ALS working with an intake bypass valve feeds air directly to the exhaust manifold, where it is mixed with partially combusted gasses from the engine, thus igniting them again and spooling up the turbo.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Such a system can be made more refined than the throttle bypass system described above.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] One of the earliest systems of this type was used by the Ferrari F1 team in the 1980s.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Another well-known application of this type of anti-lag system was in the World Rally Championship versions of the 1995 Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution III and Toyota Celica GT-Four (ST205).
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The system was controlled by two pressure valves, operated by the ECU.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Besides the racing version, the plumbing of the anti-lag system was also installed in the street-legal Celica GT-Four WRC homologation model, though the system itself was disabled, the piping and valves only present for homologation purposes.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] On later Japanese-market Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution models (IV through IX), the SAS (Secondary Air System) can be modified to provide anti-lag.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The Prodrive P2 prototype uses a more modern, refined intake bypass system.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Sometimes referred to as a Dan Culkin valve or D-valve, this is a method by which a large one-way check valve is inserted just before the throttle body, enabling air to bypass the turbo, intercooler, and charge piping during periods of negative air pressure at the throttle body inlet.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This results in a steady supply of air, allowing more fuel to combust and drive the turbine.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The valve closes as soon as positive pressure is reached in the intercooler housing.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This is less of a true anti-lag system than it is a quick spool system, and thus can be incorporated into other ALS systems.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] When used with a mass air flow sensor (MAF), the check valve should draw air through the MAF to maintain proper air-fuel ratios.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This is not necessary in a speed-density configuration.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Many programmable engine control units (ECUs) also offer an "anti-lag" feature designed to spool turbos during launches or between shifts.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] As with the aforementioned turbo bypass, this is less of a true anti-lag system than it is a quick spool system (and can also be combined with other systems), though this more closely approximates a true ALS.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] When a car is ready for launch and at its launch RPM, some ECUs (via a switch or additional throttle) can be programmed to retard the ignition by quite a few degrees and add significantly more fuel.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The combustion event occurs as the engine is driving the air/fuel mixture out of the cylinder, closer to the turbine, causing it to spool up either at a lower RPM or make much more boost at the launch RPM than it would normally.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Some software can also engage this "anti-lag" feature via clutch input with full-throttle shifting, effectively making it work between shifts.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Like other types of anti-lag, overuse of this type of anti-lag can cause damage to the turbine wheel, exhaust manifold, and more due to high pressure from the air/fuel mixture spontaneously combusting almost (or completely) outside of the combustion chamber.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This form of "anti-lag" tends to work well because it is only active at wide open throttle, during which more air can enter the engine.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Consequently, it does not perform as well (or activate at all) at partial or closed throttle, unless combined with a secondary air system or bypass as described above.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Modern Formula One engines take the form of a turbocharged V6 engine with an additional hybrid system.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] Until 2026, this hybrid system consisted of two motor–generator units (MGUs): the "Motor Generator Unit – Kinetic" (MGU-K), and the "Motor Generator Unit – Heat" (MGU-H), with the MGU-H having since been banned in the 2026 power unit regulations.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] To almost entirely eliminate turbo lag, electrical energy stored in the car's onboard battery was partially deployed to the MGU-H, which spun the compressor turbine.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This allowed the turbo system to reach peak boost pressure almost immediately, effectively negating any turbo lag.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] During normal race conditions, electric motor input was gradually reduced as engine RPM increased and the exhaust gasses were able to sustain the desired boost pressures.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] During qualifying laps and sometimes strategically throughout the race, energy could be deployed to the MGU-H on demand, even when the engine was running at high RPM.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This allowed for the exhaust gasses to bypass the turbo via the wastegate.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This was said to increase power by 5–10%, although at a cost to stored energy levels.
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] The MGU-H could also be used to generate electrical energy by allowing the electric motor that usually spun the turbine to be spun by the turbo system itself, a process known as "harvesting".
[src:engine-control-unit/anti-lag] This scenario existed when exhaust gasses were being routed through the turbo and the turbo system was operating in a conventional manner.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] An **engine control unit** (**ECU**), also called an **engine control module** (**ECM**), is a device that controls various subsystems of an internal combustion engine.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] Systems commonly controlled by an ECU include the fuel injection and ignition systems.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] The earliest ECUs (used by aircraft engines in the late 1930s) were mechanical-hydraulic units; however, most 21st-century ECUs operate using digital electronics.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] In a camless piston engine (an experimental design not currently used in any production vehicles), the ECU has continuous control of when each of the intake and exhaust valves are opened and by how much.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] One of the earliest attempts to use such a unitised and automated device to manage multiple engine control functions simultaneously was created by BMW in 1939 *Kommandogerät* system used by the BMW 801 14-cylinder radial engine which powered the Focke-Wulf Fw 190 V5 fighter aircraft.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] This device replaced the six controls used to initiate hard acceleration with one control; however, the system could cause surging and stalling problems.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for controlling engines.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which used the Toshiba TLCS-12 microprocessor, entered mass production in 1975.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] The first Bosch engine management system was the Motronic 1.0, which was introduced in the 1979 BMW 7 Series (E23).
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] This system was based on the existing Bosch Jetronic fuel injection system, to which control of the ignition system was added.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] In 1981, a Delco Electronics ECU was used by several Chevrolet and Buick engines to control their fuel system (a closed-loop carburetor) and ignition system.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] By 1988, Delco Electronics was the leading producer of engine management systems, producing over 28,000 ECUs per day.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] Such systems are used for many internal combustion engines in other applications.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] In aeronautical applications, the systems are known as FADECs (Full Authority Digital Engine Controls).
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] This kind of electronic control is less common in piston-engined light fixed-wing aircraft and helicopters than in automobiles.
[src:engine-control-unit/engine-control-unit] This is due to the common configuration of a carbureted engine with a magneto ignition system that does not require electrical power generated by an alternator to run, which is considered a safety advantage.
